During the patient’s next dialysis session, postoperative day 1, she had severe pain in her chest upon catheter aspiration. A posteroanterior (PA) chest x-rays appeared to have normal placement of a tunneled catheter with the tip at the SVC-right atrial junction (Figure 1
). Secondary to the severe pain that occurred with aspiration and flushing of the catheter, a computed tomography (CT) of the chest was performed. Axial image demonstrated the tip of the catheter was malpositioned in the right internal mammary vein (Figure 2
). The patient had bedside removal of the catheter and subsequent placement of a new catheter again via a jugular approach which was uneventful and functioned normally.
